history_of_steps.agent_output: Lagos is located in Nigeria and is known as the Lagosian. The city's motto is 'Èkó ò ní bàjé o!'. Lagos is the largest city in Nigeria and holds the same distinction in the African Union. It served as the capital for Lagos Colony, Colonial Nigeria, and the Federation of Nigeria. The total area of Lagos is 1171.28 square kilometers, with a land area of approximately 999.6 million square meters, a metro area of 2706.7 square kilometers, and an urban area measuring 907 square kilometers. The city has a total population of 8,048,430 and a metropolitan population of around 21,320,000, resulting in a population density of 6,871 people per square kilometer and a metro density of 7,759 people per square kilometer. Lagos operates on West Africa Time with a UTC offset of +1. The city was founded by the Awori tribe. Known for its airports, Lagos is served by Cally Air, Ibom Air, and Max Air, with ADC Airlines as a hub airline. Production and assembly activities in Lagos include the Volkswagen Beetle, Volkswagen Jetta (A2), and Isuzu Forward. The city is associated with notable educational figures such as Desmond Majekodunmi, Buchi Emecheta, and Habeeb Okunola. Significant city locations include the Benin-Ore-Shagamu Expressway, Encomium Magazine, and Bogobiri House, while regional health facilities include First Consultant Hospital and the National Orthopaedic Hospital in Igbobi. The area is served by GIG Mobility and hosts TEDxLagos, alongside football grounds for MFM F.C., ACB Lagos F.C., and COD United F.C. Prominent residents include Patrick Utomi, Dakuku Peterside, and Mudashiru Obasa, along with notable hometown figures like Sasha P, Davina Oriakhi, and VanJess. Important locations in Lagos include the Benfruit Plant and the Nigerian Institute of Management, as well as urban entities such as the United Africa Company of Nigeria, Promasidor Nigeria, and G-Worldwide Entertainment. The city is also home to LADOL and is nearest to the Atlantic Ocean and Lagos Lagoon. Noteworthy foundation places include Dobox and IROKO Partners, while significant buildings reflect the legacies of Isaac Fola-Alade and Olufemi Majekodunmi. Lagos is known for individuals like Olu Amoda and Toki Mabogunje, and its cultural impact includes recordings such as 'Let Me Roll It,' 'Mamunia,' and 'Band on the Run.' The city has been the birthplace and death place of various notable individuals, with births including Cait O'Riordan, Candy Augustine Agbane, and actress Carol King, and deaths including Amusa Shittu, Samuel Ajayi Crowther, and historian Samuel Johnson.

The total area of Lagos is 1171.28 square kilometers, with a land area of approximately 999.6 million square meters, a metro area of 2706.7 square kilometers, and an urban area measuring 907 square kilometers. The city has a total population of 8,048,430 and a metropolitan population of around 21,320,000, resulting in a population density of 6,871 people per square kilometer and a metro density of 7,759 people per square kilometer. Lagos operates on West Africa Time with a UTC offset of +1. The city was founded by the Awori tribe. Known for its airports, Lagos is served by Cally Air, Ibom Air, and Max Air, with ADC Airlines as a hub airline. Production and assembly activities in Lagos include the Volkswagen Beetle, Volkswagen Jetta (A2), and Isuzu Forward. The city is associated with notable educational figures such as Desmond Majekodunmi, Buchi Emecheta, and Habeeb Okunola. Significant city locations include the Benin-Ore-Shagamu Expressway, Encomium Magazine, and Bogobiri House, while regional health facilities include First Consultant Hospital and the National Orthopaedic Hospital in Igbobi. The city is also home to LADOL and is nearest to the Atlantic Ocean and Lagos Lagoon. Noteworthy foundation places include Dobox and IROKO Partners, while significant buildings reflect the legacies of Isaac Fola-Alade and Olufemi Majekodunmi. Lagos is known for individuals like Olu Amoda and Toki Mabogunje, and its cultural impact includes recordings such as 'Let Me Roll It,' 'Mamunia,' and 'Band on the Run.' The city has been the birthplace and death place of various notable individuals, with births including Cait O'Riordan, Candy Augustine Agbane, and actress Carol King, and deaths including Amusa Shittu, Samuel Ajayi Crowther, and historian Samuel Johnson.

Lagos is located in Nigeria and is known as the Lagosian. The city's motto is 'Èkó ò ní bàjé o!'. Lagos is the largest city in Nigeria and holds the same distinction in the African Union. It served as the capital for Lagos Colony, Colonial Nigeria, and the Federation of Nigeria. The total area of Lagos is 1171.28 square kilometers, with a land area of approximately 999.6 million square meters, a metro area of 2706.7 square kilometers, and an urban area measuring 907 square kilometers. The city has a total population of 8,048,430 and a metropolitan population of around 21,320,000, resulting in a population density of 6,871 people per square kilometer and a metro density of 7,759 people per square kilometer. Lagos operates on West Africa Time with a UTC offset of +1. The city was founded by the Awori tribe. Known for its airports, Lagos is served by Cally Air, Ibom Air, and Max Air, with ADC Airlines as a hub airline. Production and assembly activities in Lagos include the Volkswagen Beetle, Volkswagen Jetta (A2), and Isuzu Forward. The city is associated with notable educational figures such as Desmond Majekodunmi, Buchi Emecheta, and Habeeb Okunola. Significant city locations include the Benin-Ore-Shagamu Expressway, Encomium Magazine, and Bogobiri House, while regional health facilities include First Consultant Hospital and the National Orthopaedic Hospital in Igbobi. The area is served by GIG Mobility and hosts TEDxLagos, alongside football grounds for MFM F.C., ACB Lagos F.C., and COD United F.C. Prominent residents include Patrick Utomi, Dakuku Peterside, and Mudashiru Obasa, along with notable hometown figures like Sasha P, Davina Oriakhi, and VanJess. Important locations in Lagos include the Benfruit Plant and the Nigerian Institute of Management, as well as urban entities such as the United Africa Company of Nigeria, Promasidor Nigeria, and G-Worldwide Entertainment. The city is also home to LADOL and is nearest to the Atlantic Ocean and Lagos Lagoon. Noteworthy foundation places include Dobox and IROKO Partners, while significant buildings reflect the legacies of Isaac Fola-Alade and Olufemi Majekodunmi. Lagos is known for individuals like Olu Amoda and Toki Mabogunje, and its cultural impact includes recordings such as 'Let Me Roll It,' 'Mamunia,' and 'Band on the Run.' The city has been the birthplace and death place of various notable individuals, with births including Cait O'Riordan, Candy Augustine Agbane, and actress Carol King, and deaths including Amusa Shittu, Samuel Ajayi Crowther, and historian Samuel Johnson.

The city has been the birthplace and death place of various notable individuals, with births including Cait O'Riordan, Candy Augustine Agbane, and actress Carol King, and deaths including Amusa Shittu, Samuel Ajayi Crowther, and historian Samuel Johnson.
